Non-linear Hypotheses

Em uma classificao, para se obter um bom modelo de regresso logstica que se ajusta bem aos dados necessrios acrescentar polinmios de diversas ordens ao clculo da hiptese. Em geral, esses polinmios crescem assintoticamente na ordem de O(n^2/2), o que significa que em um modelo de 10 features de grau 2 teremos um polinmio com 66 termos . Se aumentarmos o grau do polinmio para 3, teremos 286 features.

Se ao invs de 10, tivssemos 100 features, teramos 5.151 termos considerando apenas um polinmio de grau 2 e 176.851 termos para um polinmio de grau 3.

Assim teremos um grande risco de sobreajustar o modelo, alm de ser computacionalmente caro fazer isso.

Pensando numa aplicao de reconhecimento de imagens, uma imagem pequena de 50x50 pixels tem 2500 pixels. Se tentssemos resolver com a regresso logstica, usando polinmios de grau 2, teramos um polinmio com 3.128.751 milhes de termos.

Model Representation I

Let's examine how we will represent a hypothesis function using neural networks. At a very simple level, neurons are basically computational units that take inputs (dendrites) as electrical inputs (called "spikes") that are channeled to outputs (axons). In our model, our dendrites are like the input features x1xnx_1\cdots x_nx1xn, and the output is the result of our hypothesis function. In this model our x0x_0x0 input node is sometimes called the "bias unit." It is always equal to 1. In neural networks, we use the same logistic function as in classification, 11+eTx\frac{1}{1 + e^{-\theta^Tx}}1+eTx1, yet we sometimes call it a sigmoid (logistic) activation function. In this situation, our "theta" parameters are sometimes called "weights".

Visually, a simplistic representation looks like:

[x0x1x2][   ]h(x)
x0x1x2
\rightarrow
[   ]
\rightarrow h_\theta(x)[x0x1x2][   ]h(x)

Our input nodes (layer 1), also known as the "input layer", go into another node (layer 2), which finally outputs the hypothesis function, known as the "output layer".

We can have intermediate layers of nodes between the input and output layers called the "hidden layers."

In this example, we label these intermediate or "hidden" layer nodes a02an2a^2_0 \cdots a^2_na02an2 and call them "activation units."

a(j)i="activation" of unit i in layer j(j)=matrix of weights controlling function mapping from layer j to layer j+1

If we had one hidden layer, it would look like:

[x0x1x2x3][a1(2)a2(2)a3(2)]h(x)
x0x1x2x3
\rightarrow
a(2)1a(2)2a(2)3
\rightarrow h_\theta(x)[x0x1x2x3][a1(2)a2(2)a3(2)]h(x)

The values for each of the "activation" nodes is obtained as follows:

a(2)1=g((1)10x0+(1)11x1+(1)12x2+(1)13x3)a(2)2=g((1)20x0+(1)21x1+(1)22x2+(1)23x3)a(2)3=g((1)30x0+(1)31x1+(1)32x2+(1)33x3)h(x)=a(3)1=g((2)10a(2)0+(2)11a(2)1+(2)12a(2)2+(2)13a(2)3)

This is saying that we compute our activation nodes by using a 34 matrix of parameters. We apply each row of the parameters to our inputs to obtain the value for one activation node. Our hypothesis output is the logistic function applied to the sum of the values of our activation nodes, which have been multiplied by yet another parameter matrix (2)\Theta^{(2)}(2) containing the weights for our second layer of nodes.

Each layer gets its own matrix of weights, (j)\Theta^{(j)}(j).

The dimensions of these matrices of weights is determined as follows:

If network has sj units in layer j and sj+1 units in layer j+1, then (j) will be of dimension sj+1(sj+1).\text{If network has $s_j$ units in layer $j$ and $s_{j+1}$ units in layer $j+1$, then $\Theta^{(j)}$ will be of dimension $s_{j+1} \times (s_j + 1)$.}If network has sj units in layer j and sj+1 units in layer j+1, then (j) will be of dimension sj+1(sj+1).

The +1 comes from the addition in (j)\Theta^{(j)}(j) of the "bias nodes," x0x_0x0 and 0(j)\Theta_0^{(j)}0(j). In other words the output nodes will not include the bias nodes while the inputs will. The following image summarizes our model representation:

Example: If layer 1 has 2 input nodes and layer 2 has 4 activation nodes. Dimension of (1)\Theta^{(1)}(1) is going to be 43 where sj=2s_j = 2sj=2 and sj+1=4s_{j+1} = 4sj+1=4, so sj+1(sj+1)=43s_{j+1} \times (s_j + 1) = 4 \times 3sj+1(sj+1)=43.

Model Representation II

To re-iterate, the following is an example of a neural network:

a(2)1=g((1)10x0+(1)11x1+(1)12x2+(1)13x3)a(2)2=g((1)20x0+(1)21x1+(1)22x2+(1)23x3)a(2)3=g((1)30x0+(1)31x1+(1)32x2+(1)33x3)h(x)=a(3)1=g((2)10a(2)0+(2)11a(2)1+(2)12a(2)2+(2)13a(2)3)

In this section we'll do a vectorized implementation of the above functions. We're going to define a new variable zk(j)z_k^{(j)}zk(j) that encompasses the parameters inside our g function. In our previous example if we replaced by the variable z for all the parameters we would get:

a(2)1=g(z(2)1)a(2)2=g(z(2)2)a(2)3=g(z(2)3)

In other words, for layer j=2 and node k, the variable z will be:

zk(2)=k,0(1)x0+k,1(1)x1++k,n(1)xnz_k^{(2)} = \Theta_{k,0}^{(1)}x_0 + \Theta_{k,1}^{(1)}x_1 + \cdots + \Theta_{k,n}^{(1)}x_nzk(2)=k,0(1)x0+k,1(1)x1++k,n(1)xn

The vector representation of x and zjz^{j}zj is:

x=x0x1xnz(j)=z(j)1z(j)2z(j)n

Setting x=a(1)x = a^{(1)}x=a(1), we can rewrite the equation as:

z(j)=(j1)a(j1)z^{(j)} = \Theta^{(j-1)}a^{(j-1)}z(j)=(j1)a(j1)

We are multiplying our matrix (j1)\Theta^{(j-1)}(j1) with dimensions sj(n+1)s_j\times (n+1)sj(n+1) (where sjs_jsj is the number of our activation nodes) by our vector a(j1)a^{(j-1)}a(j1) with height (n+1). This gives us our vector z(j)z^{(j)}z(j) with height sjs_jsj. Now we can get a vector of our activation nodes for layer j as follows:

a(j)=g(z(j))a^{(j)} = g(z^{(j)})a(j)=g(z(j))

Where our function g can be applied element-wise to our vector z(j)z^{(j)}z(j).

We can then add a bias unit (equal to 1) to layer j after we have computed a(j)a^{(j)}a(j). This will be element a0(j)a_0^{(j)}a0(j) and will be equal to 1. To compute our final hypothesis, let's first compute another z vector:

z(j+1)=(j)a(j)z^{(j+1)} = \Theta^{(j)}a^{(j)}z(j+1)=(j)a(j)

We get this final z vector by multiplying the next theta matrix after (j1)\Theta^{(j-1)}(j1) with the values of all the activation nodes we just got. This last theta matrix (j)\Theta^{(j)}(j) will have only one row which is multiplied by one column a(j)a^{(j)}a(j) so that our result is a single number. We then get our final result with:

h(x)=a(j+1)=g(z(j+1))h_\Theta(x) = a^{(j+1)} = g(z^{(j+1)})h(x)=a(j+1)=g(z(j+1))

Notice that in this last step, between layer j and layer j+1, we are doing exactly the same thing as we did in logistic regression. Adding all these intermediate layers in neural networks allows us to more elegantly produce interesting and more complex non-linear hypotheses.

  • Para a camada 3:

    • a(3): vetor com os valores dos neurnios da camada, de dimenso 3.

Sendo o vetor a1 os valores da camada 1 (a1 = x, onde a dimenso do vetor n+1 (+1 por causa da camada de vis)), o vetor a2 (valores dos neurnios da segunda camada) ser igual a aplicar a funo de ativao g(z) (sigmide) no vetor (dimenso n + 1) resultante do produto escalar entre a matriz de pesos Θ1 e o vetor a1.

Examples and Intuitions I

A simple example of applying neural networks is by predicting x1x_1x1 AND x2x_2x2, which is the logical 'and' operator and is only true if both x1x_1x1 and x2x_2x2 are 1.

The graph of our functions will look like:

x0x1x2[g(z(2))]h(x)

Remember that x0x_0x0 is our bias variable and is always 1.

Let's set our first theta matrix as:

(1)=[302020]\Theta^{(1)} =
[302020]
(1)=[302020]

This will cause the output of our hypothesis to only be positive if both x1x_1x1 and x2x_2x2 are 1. In other words:

h(x)=g(30+20x1+20x2)x1=0  and  x2=0  then  g(30)0x1=0  and  x2=1  then  g(10)0x1=1  and  x2=0  then  g(10)0x1=1  and  x2=1  then  g(10)1

So we have constructed one of the fundamental operations in computers by using a small neural network rather than using an actual AND gate. Neural networks can also be used to simulate all the other logical gates. The following is an example of the logical operator 'OR', meaning either x1x_1x1 is true or x2x_2x2 is true, or both:

Examples and Intuitions II

The (1)^{(1)}(1) matrices for AND, NOR, and OR are:

AND:(1)NOR:(1)OR:(1)=[302020]=[102020]=[102020]

We can combine these to get the XNOR logical operator (which gives 1 if x1x_1x1 and x2x_2x2 are both 0 or both 1).

x0x1x2a(2)1a(2)2[a(3)]h(x)

For the transition between the first and second layer, we'll use a (1)^{(1)}(1) matrix that combines the values for AND and NOR:

(1)=[302020102020]\Theta^{(1)} =
[301020202020]
(1)=[302020102020]

For the transition between the second and third layer, we'll use a (2)^{(2)}(2) matrix that uses the value for OR:

(2)=[102020]\Theta^{(2)} =
[102020]
(2)=[102020]

Let's write out the values for all our nodes:

a(2)=g((1)x)a(3)=g((2)a(2))h(x)=a(3)

R.: 60
